<h1>@HI{{no}} (nominaliser)</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vru{{}} @EM{{@HI{{no}}}}
<li> @Ai{{}} @EM{{@HI{{no}}}}
<li> @Ana{{}} @EM{{@HI{{no}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{no}}}} turns a whole sentence into a noun phrase which can then be used anywhere that a noun
phrase can normally be used.
</p>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{no}}}} cannot occur in position B of the sentence pattern:
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A@HI{{ha}} B @HI{{desu}}.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
nominalised sentences are subordinate clauses and so @HI{{ha}} cannot appear and usually becomes either
@HI{{ga}} or @HI{{no}}.
</p>

<p>
Unlike the nominaliser <a href="grammar-koto-nominaliser.html">@HI{{koto}}</a>, @EM{{@HI{{no}}}} tends to indicate
something to which the speaker does not feel very close.
</p>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{no}}}} tends to be used when the nominalised clause indicates something concrete or perceptible
whereas <a href="grammar-koto-nominaliser.html">@HI{{koto}}</a> tends to be used when it indicates something
abstract or imperceptible.
</p>


<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{tenisu}}wo suru@EM{{no}}ha omoshiroidesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Playing tennis is fun.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{cow^milk}}wo @KJ{{buy}}u@EM{{no}}wo @KJ{{forget}}remashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I forgot to buy milk.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{no}}}} is used in various cases:
<ul>
<li> @Vru{{}} @HI{{@EM{{no}}ha}} <em>adjective</em> @HI{{desu}}.
<li> @Vru{{}} @HI{{@EM{{no}}ga}} <em>adjective</em> @HI{{desu}}.
<li> @Vru{{}} @HI{{@EM{{no}}wo}} @KJ{{forget}}@HI{{remashita}}.
<li> @Vplain{{}} @HI{{@EM{{no}}wo}} @KJ{{know}}@HI{{tte imasuka}}.
</ul>
</p>

